\begin_layout Abstract
Status motivations for consumption have generated an immense interest in
 the developed economies at a time when social mobility has been relatively
 stagnant.
 Considering a setting where income inequalities are stronger and status
 rewards may comprise of simple improvements in wealth - we focus on a status
 game in the developing economies that provides future economic gain to
 the consumer.
 Viewing status as an expected future wealth in the game where consumers
 invest for status and transition through fixed bands corresponding to varied
 incomes , we examine the effect of rise in income inequalities on status
 consumption - finding that the stability of population in bands alone may
 be enough to limit status consumption in the long-term.
\end_layout

