\begin_layout Standard
The consumer response to relative income has appealed to economists since
 at least as far back as 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "VeblenLeisureClass"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 While the post-war period of relative stability and life-style improvements
 have renewed an interest in the positional concerns (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "FrankPond,HirschSocialLimits"
literal "false"

\end_inset

), there remains a disconnect between the descriptive theories - which explain
 the effects of a consumer's social context on her choices - and the theories
 of long-term economic growth (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "KayRadicalUncertainty2020,SanjitDhamiBehavioural2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 Status competitions have been argued to be ubiquitous - but the empirical
 explorations of how the microeconomic behaviour of a status-seeking consumer
 could relate with the economic growth or inequality in the developing economies
 are rare (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "KnellInequalityStatusGrowth1999,HopkinsStatusInequalityGrowth2004,CorneoStatusGrowth2001"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for theoretical arguments).
 To assist such analyses, the presented chapter addresses two questions
 pertaining to inequality and growth in the context of status comeptitions.
 First, we answer if status consumption - treated as investments towards
 future probable success - should increase or decrease with a rise in income
 inequality or not.
 Second, we clarify if income inequality may discourage risk-taking and
 contribute to growth through status competitions in the long-term.
 In addressing these questions, we focus on status games that provide a
 positive externality or direct gains to the consumer in a developing economy
 - while treating the uncertainty in intergenerational or spatial mobility
 explicitly as probabilistic rewards from investments towards status.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The stylised model of a status game with gains that are constrained with
 the long-term stability of consumer populations - pursues a contest-theory
 approach (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "TullockEfficientRentSeeking2001"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) while also bearing similarity with the model proposed by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ColeMaliathSocialNorms1992"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 where status is viewed as a ranking device for non-transactional environments
 directly influencing the consumer income.
 Equating the status goals of the consumer with her economic goals, the
 current approach views status as the expected secure wealth maximised by
 the consumer.
 It then treats status consumption as the expenditure or cost to participate
 in a tiered rewards game.
 While the approach may be of limited value in discussions where status
 consumption is treated as necessarily futile, the view of status consumption
 as investments towards material status is more relevant for growing economies
 that provide new opportunities to gain wealth amidst an environment of
 severe income inequalities.
\end_layout

