\begin_layout Standard
The second question examines if an increase in status consumption could
 result in more or less growth - which is interpreted as the consumer's
 steady-state asset accumulation in the model.
 The debates on the relationship between inequality and growth in the literature
 are both well-known and divisive.
 The conventional wisdom has relied on the early works from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "KuznetsEconomicGrowthIneq2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 who had argued that inequality rises in a country's early (agrarian) stages
 of economic development before declining as its economy matures (industrialises
).
 However, later empirical works have argued for both positive and negative
 effects of inequality on growth.
 Those who argue for a positive effect of inequality on growth emphasise
 how inequality helps innovation (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "FoellmiZweimullerIncomedistribInnovations2006"
literal "false"

