\begin_layout Standard
We had set ourselves to find how income inequality could influence growth
 and status consumption in an economy.
 Interpreting growth as asset accumulations and status consumption as investment
s or efforts spent towards economic status, we use a two-band economy under
 the conditions of population stability and a known ordering of asset utilities
 for consumers to argue that a rise in income inequalities need not always
 raise status consumption in the long-term.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
More particularly, we find that the conditions that population stability
 must prevail in a long-term equilibrium of income bands and that there
 exists a known ordering for asset utilities - together lead to two key
 implications for expenditure towards status.
 First, the expenditure towards status for the poorer (richer) consumer
 need not rise (fall) with increase in income differences.
 Second, a segregation of demand is likely for status competitions under
 inequalities when either the poorer consumer sees no benefits from participatin
g in status competitions or the rich person finds too little security on
 offer from status competitions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While it is tempting to argue using the short-term equilibrium conditions
 that wider income differences make status competitions more stringent and
 the expenditure towards status higher (lower) for the poorer (richer) consumer,
 the long-term equilibrium - under conditions of population stability alone
 - imply a different dynamics where wide income differences could reduce
 expenditure towards status by making promotion difficult (for the poor
 consumers) or security cheaper (for the richer consumers).
 This also means that the growth in the economy - interpreted as the asset
 accumulations of the consumer - might either rise or fall with higher income
 inequality.
\end_layout

